Extrinsic Materials Overview   esrailbblhs@gmail.com write down your understanding about extrinsic materials;  Extrinsic materials are materials that have been intentionally modified by adding impurities or dopants to their crystal structure to alter their electrical or optical properties. These impurities or dopants can be introduced through various techniques, such as diffusion, ion implantation, or chemical vapor deposition.  The introduction of impurities changes the electronic structure of the material, which can affect its conductivity, resistivity, and other properties. For example, adding impurities to a semiconductor material can create p-type or n-type semiconductors, which have different electrical properties and can be used for different applications.  Extrinsic materials are commonly used in the semiconductor industry to create electronic devices such as transistors, diodes, and solar cells. They can also be used in other applications such as optoelectronics, sensors, and catalysis.  Overall, extrinsic materials offer a way to tailor the properties of a material to suit a specific application, making them an essential component of modern technology.
Extrinsic material that does not form part of an act but that may assist in the interpretation of that act.

After some experiments, scientists observed an increase in the conductivity of a Semiconductor when a small amount of impurity was added to it. These materials are Extrinsic Semiconductors or impurity Semiconductors. Another term for these materials is Doped Semiconductor. The impurities are dopants and the process  Doping.  An important condition to doping is that the amount of impurity added should not change the lattice structure of the Semiconductor. To achieve this the size of the dopant and Semiconductor atoms should be the same.These dopants give rise to two types of semiconductors:  n-type & p-type

An extrinsic semiconductor is a semiconductor doped by a specific impurity which is able to deeply modify its electrical properties, making it suitable for electronic applications or optoelectronic applications

A half-wave rectifier uses a single diode to allow current to flow in only one direction during the positive half-cycle of the input AC voltage. During the negative half-cycle, the diode is reverse-biased and does not conduct any current. As a result, the output waveform is a pulsating DC waveform with half the amplitude of the input waveform.A full-wave rectifier, on the other hand, uses two diodes and a center-tapped transformer to allow current to flow in only one direction during both the positive and negative half-cycles of the input AC voltage. This results in a rectified output waveform with a higher average DC voltage compared to a half-wave rectifier.
In summary, the main difference between a half-wave and a full-wave rectifier is that a half-wave rectifier uses only one diode to rectify the positive half-cycle of the input waveform, while a full-wave rectifier uses two diodes and a center-tapped transformer to rectify both the positive and negative half-cycles of the input waveform.

Differences Between Half Wave and Full Wave Rectifier

    1)The significant key difference between half wave and full wave rectifier is efficiency. Half wave rectifier is a low-efficiency rectifier while the full wave is a high-efficiency rectifier. Thus, it is always better to use full wave when we are working on the highly efficient application.
    2)The centre tapping also differs in half wave and full wave rectifier. Half wave rectifier does not require centre tapping of the secondary winding of transformer while full wave requires centre tapping of the secondary winding of the transformer.
    3)The requirement of components varies in Half Wave and Full Wave Rectifier. Full wave requires more electronic components as compared to half wave. Thus, full wave rectifier is costly as compared to half wave. Full wave requires double the number of diodes.
